list.item:
When it is documented, we are now documenting the source of the Sanskrit term (whether it came from a dictionary, source text, etc.) with a
                @type attribute. If these were noted in the glossaries 3rd column correctly, the type should be automatically be generated by the script. For
                further details see "Appendix C.2 ."

An XPath Query that will locate any CJK unicode character that does not have an ancestor element with @xml:lang="zh" or "ja":
                //text()[matches(.,
                '&#x4E00;-&#x9FFF;&#x3040;-&#x309F;&#x30A0;-&#x30FF;&#xAC00;-&#xD7AF;')][not(ancestor::*[@xml:lang=('zh') or
                @xml:lang =('ja') or @xml:lang=('ko')])]

div.p:
Note that the milestone numbers displayed in the text are automatically generated, so the first section/chapter will display: 1.1, 1.2, 1.3, etc.
          However, the number after the period can be modified in the milestone with the @n attribute, and the initial section number may be modified in the div with a
          @prefix attribute. See these examples in the layout checks.
